Reasoning: The paper deals with algorithms for computing dynamic time warping distance, which is a problem in time series analysis and falls under the category of data structures (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also presents an approximation algorithm, which involves techniques from information theory (cs.IT). The use of well-separated tree metrics suggests that computational geometry (cs.CG) may also be relevant. Finally, the paper discusses reductions from computing edit distance and longest common subsequence length, which are problems in computational complexity (cs.CC).
